AND what Method, better suited to answer these noble Ends, could possibly have been devised, than that which the Lord their God took, for the Space of forty Years in the Wilderness: Wherein he humbled them, and proved them, and tried them, that it might appear what was in their Hearts: and he left them to hunger and to thirst, and to murmur and rebel, and to commit Idolatry, that their Hearts might be turned inside out before their Eyes: and by a long Course of Discipline, he trained them up to a Sense of his Being, and Perfections, and Government, and to feel their Dependance on him, and Obligations to him, and by Experience learn the dreadful Nature of Sin. He fed them with Angels Food, and gave them Water out of the flinty Rock: he led them by Day in a Cloud, and in the Night by a Pillar of Fire: but when they rebelled, the Earth opened its Mouth, and swallowed up Hundreds, and the Plague swept away Thousands at a Stroke; 
                  〈◊〉
                at last, the whole Congregation of Six Hundred Thousand were doomed to fall in the Wilderness.
